The best approach for `File.ReadAllText`, `File.WriteAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides mockable interfaces for all of these.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs / Startup.cs
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

// File.ReadAllText
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

// File.WriteAllText
manager.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists
Assert.True(manager.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
Assert.False(manager.EnsureDirectory("/missing"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**
- Covers the entire `System.IO` surface — you won't need to expand the interface as you use more file APIs
- `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory file system out of the box — no mocking framework needed
- Widely adopted, well-maintained, and handles edge cases you'd have to solve yourself

Once installed, use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill (or ask me) to bulk-replace existing `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites with the injected `IFileSystem`.
